quest_title: A man walks 4 km due north in one hour and 3 km due east in the next hour. The average velocity of man is
explanation_txt:
For north

\(\begin{aligned} \overrightarrow{\mathrm{S}_{1}} &=4 \mathrm{km} \\ \overrightarrow{\mathrm{S}_{2}} &=3 \mathrm{km} \\ \text { Total time }(\mathrm{t}) &=\mathrm{t}_{1}+\mathrm{t}_{2} \\ &=1+1=2 \mathrm{h} \end{aligned}\)

\(\begin{array}{l}{\text { Total displacement }(\mathrm{s})=\sqrt{\mathrm{S}_{1}^{2}+\mathrm{S}_{2}^{2}}} \\ {\qquad \begin{aligned} &=\sqrt{4^{2}+3^{2}}=5 \mathrm{km} \\ \text { Average velocity }(v) &=\cfrac{\mathrm{s}}{\mathrm{t}}=\cfrac{5}{2}=2.5 \mathrm{km} / \mathrm{hr} \end{aligned}}\end{array}\)

\(\begin{array}{l}{\tan \alpha=\cfrac{\mathrm{S}_{2}}{\mathrm{S}_{1}}=\cfrac{3}{4}} \\ {\alpha=\operatorname{Tan}^{-1}(3 / 4)=37^{\circ}} \\ {\therefore 2.5 \mathrm{km} / \mathrm{hr} \text { at } 37^{\circ} \text { east of north. }}\end{array}\)
question_plain_title: A man walks 4 km due north in one hour and 3 km due east in the next hour. The average velocity of man is
explanation_plain_text: For north
ans1_plain_text: 2.5 km/hr 37 east of North
ans2_plain_text: 3.5 km/hr 37 North of East
ans3_plain_text: 5 km/hr 37 East of North
ans4_plain_text: 2.5 km/hr 37 North of East

quest_title: In hydrogen atom, the electron makes \(6.6 \times 10 ^ { 15 }\) revolutions per second around the nucleus in an orbit of radius \(0.5 \times 10 ^ { - 10 } m\). It is equivalent to a current nearly
explanation_txt:
Current flowing through a section = Charge flowing through it in a second

If a charge q rotates in an orbit with frequency f, number of charge flowing through a section in the orbit per second is the product of charge times the frequency (number of times the charge passes through the section).

i.e. \(I = q f = 1.6 \times 10 ^ { - 19 } \times 6.6 \times 10 ^ { 15 } = 10.56 \times 10 ^ { - 4 } A = 1 m A\)

quest_title: A magnet of magnetic moment \({M}\) is lying in a magnetic field induction \({B}\). \({W}\)\({}_{1}\) is the work done in turning it from 0\(^ \circ\) to 60\(^ \circ\) and \({W}\)\({}_{2}\) is the work done in turning it from 30\(^ \circ\) to 90\(^ \circ\). Then
explanation_txt:
\(W = MB(\cos \theta_1-\cos \theta_2) \)

\( \therefore \, W_1 = MB ( \cos 0^\circ - \cos 60^\circ) = \cfrac{1}{2} MB \)

& \( W_2 = MB( \cos 30^ \circ - \cos 90^ \circ) = \cfrac{\sqrt 3}{2} MB \)

\( \therefore \, W_2 = \sqrt{3}W_1 \)

quest_title: The wavelength of first member of Balmer series is 6563\(\mathring{A}\) then wavelength of second member of same series is
explanation_txt:
For \(1^{\text {st }}\) member of Balmer series
\(\cfrac{1}{\lambda_{B}}=R\left[\cfrac{1}{4}-\cfrac{1}{9}\right]\)
or, \(\cfrac{1}{\lambda_{B}}=\cfrac{5 R}{36}\)
Or, \(\lambda_{B}=\cfrac{36}{5 R} \quad \cdots \cdots \cdots(1)\)
For \(2^{\text {nd }}\) member of same series
\(\cfrac{1}{\lambda_{\mathrm{B}^{\prime}}}=\mathrm{R}\left[\cfrac{1}{4}-\cfrac{1}{16}\right]\)
or, \(\cfrac{1}{\lambda_{\mathrm{B}^{\prime}}}=\mathrm{R}\left[\cfrac{4-1}{16}\right]\)
or, \(\lambda_{\mathrm{B}^{\prime}}=\cfrac{16}{3 \mathrm{R}} \ldots \ldots \ldots . .(2)\)
Dividing ( 2) \(\mathrm{by}(1)\)
\(\cfrac{\lambda_{\mathrm{B}}^{\prime}}{\lambda_{\mathrm{B}}}=\cfrac{16}{3 \mathrm{R}} \times \cfrac{5 \mathrm{R}}{36}\)
or, \(\lambda_{\mathrm{B}}^{\prime}=\cfrac{16 \times 5}{3 \times 36} \times 6563=4862 \mathrm{A}\)
